          "body": "At the center of the psalm's petition (v. 8) David reaches for two of the most intimate protection-images in Scripture. 'Keep me as the apple of the eye' — *ishon bat-ayin*, literally 'the little man of the daughter of the eye,' the pupil, the most guarded part of the most guarded organ. The eye instinctively closes at the slightest threat to the pupil; it is the body's reflex of automatic, involuntary protection. David is asking God to treat him the way the body treats the pupil — with instinctive, non-negotiable protection. The second image — 'hide me in the shadow of Your wings' — reaches for the tenderness of the parent bird covering its young (cf. Deuteronomy 32:10-11, where the identical phrase appears for God's care of Israel in the wilderness). Both images operate simultaneously: the first speaks to *precious worth* (the pupil is guarded because it is irreplaceable), the second to *vulnerable smallness* (the chick shelters because it cannot protect itself). Together they capture the believer's paradox: infinitely valued and completely dependent. Jesus explicitly takes up the second image for His own longing over Jerusalem in Matthew 23:37, showing that the protective wing is Christological as well as Yahwistic."
