        "body": "Three verses characterize the enemy, and the portrait is carefully constructed to form the antithesis of David's self-description in verses 3-5. David's heart was open to God's testing (v. 3); their hearts are closed, literally 'fat' (*chelev*, v. 10) — a Hebrew idiom for spiritual insensibility, the calloused thickness that prevents any divine impression from getting through (cf. Isaiah 6:10; Deuteronomy 32:15). David's mouth was resolved not to transgress (v. 3); their mouths speak with arrogance (*geut*, pride, swelling). The parallelism is deliberate: inside = closed/fat heart; outside = arrogant speech. The man whose inner life is impervious to God will eventually speak accordingly.\n\nVerse 11 marks the acute temporal moment: 'They have **now** surrounded us in our steps.' The shift from singular 'me' (vv. 8-9) to plural 'us' is striking — David may be including his companions, his band of followers (as in the Saulide persecution, 1 Samuel 22), or using the plural for rhetorical emphasis. What matters is the encirclement — they have tracked every step, surrounded completely, and 'set their eyes to cast us to the ground.' The eye-imagery returns: God's eyes see with equity (v. 2), but the enemy's eyes are fixed on destruction.\n\nVerse 12 reaches for the lion simile, and it draws on two stages of predation: the mature lion (*ari*) greedy (*kasaph*, literally 'silver-lustful,' craving) for prey, and the young lion (*kephir*) in ambush (*mistar*, hiding place). The double image suggests both experienced power and patient cunning — not merely brute force but strategic, patient hunting. The historical background is David's literal years of being hunted by Saul in the Judean wilderness, where lions and wild animals were genuine hazards. But the simile has been read by every persecuted generation as the portrait of any enemy who pursues with predatory intent: 1 Peter 5:8 uses the same lion-image for the devil who 'prowls around like a roaring lion, seeking someone to devour.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chelev* (fat, v.10 — 'unfeeling heart') is the word for the fatty covering of organs offered in sacrifice; used metaphorically for insensibility to God (Psalm 119:70). *Kasaph* (greedy, v.12) is related to the word for silver — the lion craves prey the way a greedy man craves money. *Mistar* (hiding places, v.12) — concealed positions in rocky terrain, the same terrain of David's actual wilderness fugitive years."
