        "body": "Having presented evidence (vv. 1-5), stated the petition (vv. 6-9), and filed the charges against the enemy (vv. 10-12), David now calls for the verdict and its execution. Four rapid imperatives: 'Arise ... confront ... bring him low ... deliver.' The escalation mirrors the urgency of the lion in verse 12 — as the predator crouches to spring, David calls for God to rise and advance ahead of it. 'Arise, O Lord' is one of the most ancient battle-cries in Israel's worship (Numbers 10:35; Psalm 3:7; 7:6; 9:19), invoking the divine warrior who goes before His people.\n\n'Deliver my soul from the wicked with Your sword' — God's sword (*cherev*) is the instrument of judgment in Deuteronomy 32:41-42 and Isaiah 34:5-6. The divine warrior does not merely restrain the wicked; He judges them. David is not asking for personal vengeance; he is asking the Judge to execute the verdict the evidence demands. The distinction matters: imprecatory prayer is not the expression of personal malice but the appeal to divine justice to act consistently with its own character.\n\nVerse 14 then develops a striking theology of the wicked's prosperity. 'Men of the world, whose portion is in this life, and whose belly You fill with Your treasure; they are satisfied with children, and leave their abundance to their babes.' God fills them — the prosperity of the wicked is not outside His sovereignty. Their abundance is real. Their children are real. Their generational legacy is real. But their *cheleq* (portion, inheritance) is exhausted within *cheled* (this transient age). They have been given everything, and everything they have been given is temporary. Thomas Watson saw in this verse the cruelest form of divine judgment: to give men exactly what they want and nothing more — a full belly, a satisfied life, and a horizon that ends at death. The wicked are not being punished in verse 14; they are being described as receiving their entire share in the present age, with nothing in reserve. Their prosperity is not a sign of God's favor; it is the full disbursement of their inheritance.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qamay* (Arise) in v.13 links back to the same root in the enemies 'rising up against' in v.7 — God is called to rise against those who rose against David. *Cheled* (world, v.14) — the transient passing span, the brief human age, distinct from *olam* (eternity). *Cheleq* (portion) is the same word David uses in Psalm 16:5 ('The LORD is my cheleq') — the contrast between the two psalms is intentional."
